==English==
===Alternative Spellings===
:[[meter]] (chiefly U.S.)

===Etymology===
From ancient [[Greek]]: ''&#956;&#949;&#964;&#961;&#959;&#957;'' (''metron''), "[[measure]]", "rule", "length", "size", "poetic metre"; via [[Latin]] ''[[metrum]]'' (sense 1) and [[French]] ''[[mètre]]'' (sense 2).

===Pronunciation===
:[[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]: /ˈmiːtə(r)/
:[[SAMPA]]: /"mi:t@(r)/

===Noun===
'''metre''' (plural '''metres''')
# The [[rhythm]] or [[measure]] in [[verse]] and [[musical]] [[composition]].
#: '''Derived terms'''
#:* [[metronome]]
#: '''External links'''
#:* [[w:meter (poetry)|Wikipedia article: ''meter (poetry)'']]
# The basic [[unit]] of [[length]] in the [[International System of Units]] (SI: Système International d'Unités). It is defined as the [[length]] of the path travelled by [[light]] in a [[vacuum]] during a [[time]] interval of 1/299,792,458 of a [[second]]. It is equal to 39.37 [[Imperial]] [[inch]]es.
#: '''Spelling''': This, rather than ''meter'', is the spelling adopted by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures for use in its publications.
#: '''Symbol''': [[m]]
#: '''Quotations'''
#:* '''1797''' - ''The Monthly magazine and British register'', No. 3
#:*: The measures of length above the metre are ten times [etc.]...greater than the metre.
#:* '''1873''' - ''The Young Englishwoman'', April
#:*: A dress length of 8 metres of the best quality costs 58 francs.
#:* '''1928''' - ''The Observer'', April 15
#:*: The 12-metre yachts...can be sailed efficiently with four paid hands.
#: '''Derived terms'''
#:* [[metrology]]
#:* See [http://www1.bipm.org/en/si/prefixes.html SI prefixes]
#: '''External links'''
#:* [http://www1.bipm.org/en/si/base_units/metre.html International Bureau of Weights and Measures]
#:* [[w:metre|Wikipedia article: ''metre'']]

